Summary: In this assignment, I collected close price data of S&P 500 Index from 1/1/70 to 4/13/16 (mm/dd/yy), then I calculated 20 and 50 day moving average of spx data. After this, I did the following steps:
# Create a zoo object signal with column names spx, buy, sell such that (from 1/1/2014 onwards)
# spx: contains the original spx time series
# buy: has values of 0, apart from the period in which spxz_20 first crosses above spxz_50
# sell: has values of 0, apart from the period in which spxz_20 first crosses below spxz_50
Finally, I plot buy signals as green vertical lines and sell signals as red vertical lines.

1 Section 1: Loading Data

# Load spx.csv into R as variable 'spx'
spx <- read.csv('exercises_1/spx.csv', header = TRUE, sep = ',')

# convert 'spx' to a zoo time series, 'spxz'
spxz <- zoo(spx$close, as.Date(spx$date, format = '%m/%d/%Y'))
## Warning in strptime(x, format, tz = "GMT"): unknown timezone 'zone/tz/
## 2017c.1.0/zoneinfo/America/Los_Angeles'
# Plot the time series, spxz, on a chart, and give it a Title, x-Label and y-Label
plot(x = spxz, type = 'l', main = 'Time series plot of spx', xlab = 'Time', ylab = 'Spx')

2 Section 2: Calculating Returns

# Calculate daily returns of spxz, 'ret_daily'
ret_daily <- diff(spxz) / spxz[-length(spxz)]

# Calculate the Total Return, 'ret_total', over the period
ret_total <- (spx$close[nrow(spx)] - spx$close[1]) / spx$close[1]

# Calculate the log of daily returns, 'ret_log', and the sum of log returns, 'ret_log_sum' i.e.
#   ret_log_sum = log(1 + r1) + log(1 + r2) + log(1 + r3)
ret_log <- diff(log(spxz))
ret_log_sum <- sum(ret_log)

# Verify that ret_total and ret_log_sum are consistent with one another
print(exp(ret_log_sum))
## [1] 22.58657
print(ret_total + 1)
## [1] 22.58657
print('Are "ret_total" and "ret_log_sum" consistent with one another?')
## [1] "Are \"ret_total\" and \"ret_log_sum\" consistent with one another?"
print(format(ret_total + 1, digits = 5) == format(exp(ret_log_sum), digits = 5))
## [1] TRUE

3 Section 3: Manipulating Data

# Calculate the 20 and 50 day moving average of spxz, 'spxz_20' and 'spxz_50'
spxz_20 <- SMA(spxz, n = 20)
spxz_50 <- SMA(spxz, n = 50)

# Create a zoo object 'signal' with column names spx, buy, sell such that
#   spx: contains the original spx time series
#   buy: has values of 0, apart from the period in which spxz_20 *first* crosses above spxz_50
#   sell: has values of 0, apart from the period in which spxz_20 *first* crosses below spxz_50

inflect <- diff(ifelse(spxz_20 > spxz_50, 1, 0)) # searvh for inflection points of difference of 
# spxz_20 and spxz_50
buy <- ifelse(inflect == 1, 1, 0) # buy signals: all 1s 
sell <- ifelse(inflect == -1, 1, 0) # sell signals: all 1s
signal <- zoo(merge(spx = spxz[-1], merge(buy, sell)))

4 Section 4: Plotting

# -------------------

# On one plot, from 1/1/2014 onwards
#   1. plot spxz (black), spxz_20 (green), spxz_50 (blue) as a time series
#   2. plot buy signals (green) as vertical lines
#   3. plot sell signal (red) as vertical lines
#   4. show a legend in the top left for spxz, spxz_20 and spxz_50
#   5. leave the y label blank, label the x axis "Date"
#   6. give the chart a sensible name

plot(x = spxz[index(spxz) >= '2014-01-01'], type = 'l', pch = 100, xlab = 'Date', ylab = '', 
     main = 'Plot of Moving Average Crossover Strategy ')
lines(x = spxz_20[index(spxz_20) >= '2014-01-01'], type = 'l', col = 'green')
lines(x = spxz_50[index(spxz_50) >= '2014-01-01'], type = 'l', col = 'blue')
abline(v = index(signal[buy[index(buy) >= '2014-01-01'] == 1]), lty = 2, col = 'green') # vertical lines of buy signal
abline(v = index(signal[sell[index(sell) >= '2014-01-01'] == 1]), lty = 2, col = 'red') # vertical lines of sell signal 
legend('topleft', 
       c('spxz', 'spxz_20', 'spxz_50'), 
       lty = c(1, 1, 1), lwd = c(1, 1, 1), 
       col = c('black', 'green', 'blue'),
       cex = 0.8) # add legend to this graph
  
legend('bottomright', 
       c('buy', 'sell'), 
       lty = c(2, 2), lwd = c(1, 1), 
       col = c('green', 'red'),
       cex = 0.8) # add legend to this graph

5 Section 5: Output

# Output the most recent 100 data points from the chart into one csv file 'results.csv'
write.csv(tail(signal, 100), file = 'result.csv')
